AB  - Environmental criminology attempts to explain why criminals choose one crime location over another.  Evidence suggests that criminals prefer to stalk neighborhoods with which they are somewhat familiar, yet which are sufficiently populated to provide them with anonymity.  Criminals also prefer areas of the city where there is little chance that law-abiding citizens will intervene against criminal attack.  Thus, security managers must understand the "business envelope" that surrounds their location.  By answering pertinent questions from the potential criminal's point of view, security managers may assess the likelihood that their facilities would be the targets of attack.  Environmental criminologists tend to assume that property criminals will make somewhat rational choices about crime targets to maximize their profits and minimize their efforts.  An understanding of criminal thought patterns allows for the design of target hardening and other preventive efforts.
