AB  - The following dissertation explored the criminological phenomenon of home-invasion robbery by investigating the behavioral characteristics associated to perpetration. The problem considered pertained to the behavioral patterns of perpetration related to crime commission that is unknown to practitioners and law enforcement professionals. Recent studies have examined home-invasion victimization and environmental methods implemented to prevent victimization; unfortunately, little empirical research exists on the behavioral patterns of home-invasion perpetration. This study was performed to enhance and examine what was currently known about home-invasion robbery. The researcher collected and assessed approximately 20 case files of home-invasion robbery obtained from a large metropolitan police department in the southern region of the United States. Rational choice theory was integrated into the theoretical framework and recapitulated in the literature review. The literature review expounded upon aspects associated to home-invasion victimization, perpetration characteristics, the need for further research pertaining to home-invasion robbery, and the application of environmental criminology as an additional method of assessing perpetration patterns of offenders. The empirical study conducted was qualitative, with the purpose of verifying the existence of perpetration patterns of home-invasion robbery and to determine if a collective set of patterns exists among them. The researcher was able to establish a baseline for home-invasion offender typologies to include: (a) Emulator, (b) Monetarist, (c) Associate, (d) Tyrant, and (e) Consumer. Furthermore, the researcher established a set of baseline classifications of entry to include: (a) Enticer, (b) Intimidator, (c) Predator, and (d) Opportunist. Copies of dissertations may be obtained by addressing your request to ProQuest, 789 E. Eisenhower Parkway, P.O. Box 1346, Ann Arbor, MI 48106-1346. Telephone 1-800-521-3042; e