AB  - Traditionally, where our bushfires have been the product of human intervention the culprits have ranged from the careless cigarette butt disposer or backyard burn-off enthusiast to the occasional pyromaniac. Yet just as serial killers represent our image of all murderers, the demon who finds inexplicable pleasure in fire and destruction has captured the public imagination when it comes to the portrayal of the bushfire arsonist. This has coloured the debate about appropriate penalties for those caught with the matches and the kero.Pyromaniacs excluded, arsonists tend to commit the offence infrequently. When they do indulge in fire lighting wilfully, they are confident that they won't get caught. Thus the argument that tougher penalties will deter these offenders is problematic. In addition, young people involved in fire lighting may engage in this among many other forms of delinquency and destructive behaviour. With this in mind, it is the delinquent pattern of the juvenile arsonist that criminal justice must address if arson is to be controlled along with so many more common and regular forms of damage to community property. The urge to damage community property in all its forms is a disturbingly common feature of juvenile delinquency.Another consideration that the law's response to the bushfire crisis puts into stark relief is the community's expectations for punishment. I've already mentioned deterrence and its essential dependence on the fact that an offender considers the possibility of apprehension. But for deterrence to work, it must be assumed that the offender makes a rational choice to light fires, and is not intoxicated or beyond appreciating the consequences of his actions. The sheer craziness of these events challenges these assumptions.
